Railways Â· Mumbai, India

The trains that kept killing people

2014 â€” Urban Safety

Ten people died every single day on Mumbai's suburban train network. Fences, fines, and warning signs had all failed. The problem wasn't awareness â€” it was perception.

Mumbai's 7 million daily commuters share a rail network where tracks run at street level through densely populated neighbourhoods. People crossed, even as trains approached. Research revealed why: the Leibowitz effect â€” humans systematically underestimate the speed of large objects by up to 40%. Existing interventions were all rational. The behaviour was not.

75% reduction in fatalities, year one 22 locations scaled to 44% decline across Central Line stretch

The research

We investigated what was actually happening cognitively at crossing points. The Leibowitz hypothesis explained the pattern: people perceive large, slow-moving objects as being farther away than they are. A fully-loaded Mumbai local train â€” wide, familiar â€” triggered exactly this distortion. People "knew" trains were fast, but didn't feel it in the moment.

The interventions

  • Visceral fear posters: Large format photos of fear-stricken human faces placed at crossing points, bypassing rational processing to trigger an instinctive threat response.
  • Dual-horn blast: A two-tone horn pattern timed specifically to interrupt automatic behaviour and signal immediate danger.
  • Yellow rail ties: Bright yellow paint on the sleepers created a high-contrast pattern that unconsciously recalibrated speed perception â€” the stripes streamed past faster, breaking the Leibowitz illusion.

Scale & impact

After 75% fatality reduction in the first pilot year, interventions were scaled to 22 stations along the Central Railway Line. Each site showed 80â€“90% reduction. Across a 5km stretch, deaths fell from 88 to 49 in just six months.

VMMC Â· Zambia & Zimbabwe

The 90% who never came back

2015â€“2017 â€” HIV Prevention

Voluntary medical male circumcision reduces HIV transmission by 60%. Between 60â€“70% of men intended to get it done. Only 1 in 10 followed through.

The intention-behaviour gap was enormous. Men weren't avoiding VMMC out of ignorance â€” they knew the benefits. Journey mapping with 200 men per country revealed three distinct psychological stages: Relate (building trust and relevance), Anticipate (managing fear of pain and loss), and Relief (processing aftermath). Each stage had specific barriers that were never being addressed.

2,000 men surveyed per country 7+6 segments identified (ZM+ZW)

The research

Using EthnoLabâ„¢ with 200 men per country and quantitative segmentation with 2,000 participants, we mapped the full psychological journey. The research surfaced deeply held fears â€” not just pain, but fears of emasculation, loss of sexual sensation, distrust of the health system, and shame within peer groups.

The segments

Zambia yielded 7 distinct behavioural segments; Zimbabwe, 6. Each had different entry points, different fears, and required different messaging. A young man motivated by pride needed a completely different conversation than one driven by provider anxiety for his family.

The interventions

  • Pain-o-meter: A simple visual comparison tool helping men contextualise the procedure's discomfort against familiar experiences â€” directly addressing the fear of the unknown.
  • Mobiliser flipcharts: Segment-specific conversation tools for community health workers, with quick identification questions to determine which approach to use.
  • Targeted messaging: Communications designed around each segment's specific emotional context rather than generic HIV prevention framing.

Adoption

The behavioural frameworks and tools were adopted by health ministries in both Zambia and Zimbabwe for national programme design.

AGYW Â· Tanzania & South Africa

HIV prevention through relationships, not risk

2017â€“2021 â€” Adolescent Girls & HIV

Adolescent girls and young women are 8Ã— more likely to contract HIV than their male peers. Cash transfer programs and awareness campaigns weren't working. The reason: they were solving the wrong problem.

Programmes focused on HIV risk missed what young women actually thought about â€” relationships, respect, emotional security. Research in Tanzania and South Africa with thousands of participants revealed that HIV prevention needed to be embedded in the context that actually mattered to them: navigating romantic relationships on their own terms.

3,500+ stakeholders engaged 3 distinct behavioural segments 97% found workshop relevant (3mo later)

The insight

Research across both countries found that young women weren't avoiding HIV prevention because of ignorance â€” 48% thought they were already at lower risk than peers. The real barriers were relational: fear of losing a partner, desire for emotional validation, and the primacy of relationship goals over health messaging.

The three segments

Lifestyle Lulu (28%): Prioritises functional and material needs from relationships. Sees men as providers; needs messaging around self-reliance and lifestyle goals.

Affirmation Ayabonga (30%): Seeks emotional support, validation, and being understood. Fears partner abandonment if she insists on condom use.

Respect Rethabile (42%): Wants equity and to be heard. Has the self-agency but needs tools to negotiate safely in relationships.

The intervention

The Relationship Workshop: a 19-session in-person and WhatsApp programme that built women's capacity to navigate relationships before addressing HIV prevention. By anchoring the work in relationship goals, HIV protection became something women wanted â€” not something done to them.

Results

  • 97% of Respect Rethabile participants found it relevant three months later
  • Negotiation confidence rose from 79% to 94% (Lifestyle Lulu) and 87% to 98% (Respect Rethabile)
  • 100% of Lifestyle Lulu participants sought further support three months after

Why mothers weren't going to the hospital

2017â€“2020 â€” Maternal & Child Health

Women were choosing to deliver at home even when hospitals were accessible. Health workers blamed culture. The real answer was hiding in the social architecture of the household.

EthnoLab Conundrumâ„¢ sessions in Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, and Kenya surfaced a finding that disrupted the standard narrative: nurses were prioritising professional risk over patient risk, creating a systematically hostile experience. And within households, older women â€” mothers-in-law â€” held more decision-making authority over pregnancy than any health worker ever would.

6 districts researched (India + Kenya)

The research

Working across Sitapur and Bihar in India and Mathare, Kiambu, Narok, and Homa Bay in Kenya, we conducted EthnoLab Conundrumâ„¢ sessions with pregnant and breastfeeding women, household members, and healthcare workers. The Pathways Map â€” tracking vulnerabilities across a woman's entire life from early adolescence to late adulthood â€” revealed that social and environmental conditions shaped health outcomes far more than clinical access.

The hidden drivers

  • Nurses' behaviour was shaped by fear of blame and professional consequence, not indifference to patients
  • Senior women in households (mothers-in-law, aunts) held the real decision-making authority on delivery choices
  • Distorted risk perceptions meant women feared hospitals more than home birth complications
  • Internalized gender norms led women to discount their own pain and needs as normal

The interventions

Practical packaging changes â€” reframing IFA tablet labelling to signal infant benefit rather than maternal supplement â€” showed that simple message shifts could change uptake. The research also identified which family members needed to be included in health communication to shift the real decision-makers.

Sanitation Â· India

90 million toilets. Nobody using them.

2011â€“2014 â€” Open Defecation

India's government built 90 million toilets under the Nirmal Bharat Abhiyan. 340 million people still defecated in the open. Half the new toilets sat unused â€” or became storage rooms.

The standard assumption was ignorance or habit. Research in 17 Karnataka villages and Delhi slums found something more complex: toilets had accumulated powerfully negative associations â€” darkness, smell, claustrophobia, anxiety about maintenance costs. And open defecation wasn't shameful; for many, it was a communal, social experience. Shame-based interventions were therefore missing the point entirely.

17 Karnataka villages researched 3 urban slum sites (Delhi & Agra)

What the research found

Six EthnoLabâ„¢ villages and urban immersions in Delhi and Agra revealed that disgust, fear, and social ritual were the real drivers â€” not awareness. Toilets triggered visceral negative responses: darkness, confined spaces, uncertainty about maintenance. Open defecation, by contrast, was often a morning social ritual, especially for women who used it as rare unstructured outdoor time.

Rural interventions

  • Schools as levers: Toilet breaks, Gandhi storytelling sessions, and homework where children interviewed adults about defecation habits made the next generation into household advocates
  • Footprint guidance: Blue painted footprints showing correct squat position reduced uncertainty about how to use unfamiliar fixtures
  • Utility catalogue: Mirrors, shelves, decorative stickers, and plants â€” making the toilet a space people wanted to use and personalise

Urban CTC interventions

  • Soap bars, mirrors, and radios while waiting addressed the sensory experience
  • Lottery tickets for using the toilet proved highly effective, especially for children and men (the household decision-makers on toilet purchase)
  • Hand stamps and antiâ€“open defecation posters extended motivation beyond the visit

The lottery system was particularly striking: a small, unpredictable reward overcame inertia and changed first-use behaviour â€” the critical step for habit formation.

Financial Inclusion Â· India

177 million bank accounts. All of them empty.

2016â€“2018 â€” PMJDY Scheme

India's Pradhan Mantri Jan-Dhan Yojana was a triumph of financial access â€” 177 million accounts opened in three years. A year later, half were dormant, with an average balance of â‚¹1,277 ($19). Access wasn't the problem.

Immersion interviews with 60 households and EthnoLabâ„¢ with 750 participants across rural and urban India â€” from Madurai to Guwahati â€” revealed the real barrier: scarcity psychology. Average household debt was â‚¹32,000 against savings of â‚¹11,800. Not because people didn't understand interest rates, but because chronic scarcity creates cognitive tunnel vision â€” the ability to plan for the future is literally impaired when survival demands are constant.

750 EthnoLabâ„¢ participants â‚¹32K avg debt vs â‚¹11.8K savings

The key insight

People asked the wrong question: not "Is this interest rate too high?" but "Can I manage the repayment?" They understood informal lenders charged 10% per month â€” they used them anyway because the process was familiar, fast, and relationship-based. Financial literacy campaigns were solving a problem that didn't exist.

Scarcity psychology

The research drew on scarcity theory to explain the savings gap. Under chronic financial stress, people's cognitive bandwidth is consumed by immediate problems. Future-oriented decisions â€” saving, insurance, investment â€” require mental space that scarcity literally denies. Blaming lack of financial literacy misattributed the problem.

Recommendations

  • Goal-labelled savings: Repackage savings products around specific, concrete goals â€” school fees, wedding, house repair â€” rather than abstract "saving"
  • Default architecture: Auto-channel government benefits into savings and insurance with opt-out rather than opt-in
  • Credit-savings linkage: Link credit eligibility to savings track record, making the savings account itself a pathway to formal credit
  • Process literacy over financial literacy: Teach how the system works step-by-step, not economic theory

Scale

Recommendations were piloted through a CDFI and submitted to the Government of India for national-scale consideration.
